				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">I think the draft was it was used in World War II was a needed thing.
<br />

<br />
If it’s really the fate of the world or our Country, then yes, people should be obligated to defend it for the generations to come. Our forefathers made these kinds of sacrifices to create the world we live in, and I don’t see any reason not to expect that of ourselves.
<br />

<br />
I’m against War in general, and if disputes could be solved with harsh chess games then I’d be all for it.
<br />

<br />
I watched a TV show last night on public broadcasting about the 507th airborne infantry and their role in the Battle of Normandy and the Battle of the Bulge. These were guys that drove taxi cabs, taught elementary school and worked as construction workers. They were trained for 2 months in skydiving and military fighting and dropped 20 miles behind the beach head in Normandy. If the army that invaded Normandy and fought the Battle of the Bulge had been a strictly volunteer force then we (The Allies) would have either A: Lost the War or B: Fought a much longer war with greater loss of life on all sides.
<br />

<br />
It was really sad hearing the testimony of the soldiers (Now in their 80’s) and how much horror they went through to secure freedom for our world, but every one of them in the interview said they’d do it again.
<br />

<br />
In 1944 the 507th was returned to Boston and disbanded right as they landed. They all (That survived) went back to their jobs as cab drivers and teachers etc.<br />_________________<br /><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=375146" target="_blank" class="postlink">Gojirax</a> - 67 Arch Lich
<br />
<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=375178" target="_blank" class="postlink">Callean</a> - 67 Archon ~ <span style="font-style: italic">Bearer of the Water Sprinkler</span>
