				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>najiwench wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">i don't think it would remove any freedom of action or will</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Forgive me, Naji, but .... is there some part of "compulsory service" you're missing? If you are <span style="font-weight: bold">forced by law</span> -- after all, that's what "compulsory", in this context, means -- then you don't have freedom of action or will. Because, see, if you <span style="font-weight: bold">did</span> have freedom of action or will, then the service wouldn't be compulsory.
<br />

<br />
Personally, I think more young people <span style="font-weight: bold">should</span> choose to enter the military, or to perform some other sort of community service. But I think the impetus for that should come from enhanced civics education -- i.e., teaching young people what the responsibilities & rights of citizenship are -- in such a way as to motivate them to serve a country they believe in, as opposed to just holding down a government job for a couple years.
<br />

<br />
Compulsory service = slavery.<br />_________________<br />Benbow Bookbinder, 58 Elementalist, Veeshan
<br />
Mark of the Black Frog
<br />
So many books, so little time!
